    "sourceFiles": [
      "full_stack_interview_prep_deep_chatgpt_style_v2(1).html"
    ],
    "content": "## Definition\n\nA GenAI backend is an application layer that connects user input, retrieval, tools, business rules, and an LLM to produce useful outputs.\n\nCommon pieces:\n\n```text\nUser query\n  -> validation/auth\n  -> retrieval/tool selection\n  -> prompt assembly\n  -> LLM call\n  -> structured output parsing\n  -> post-processing\n  -> response + sources/logs\n```\n\n## RAG definition\n\n**Retrieval-Augmented Generation** means the application retrieves relevant external knowledge and passes it to the LLM as context.\n\n```text\nDocuments -> chunking -> embeddings -> vector DB\nUser query -> embedding -> similarity search -> context -> LLM answer\n```\n\n## Why RAG exists\n\nRAG reduces hallucination and allows the model to answer from private/current data without retraining. It is useful for knowledge bases, internal docs, policy Q&A, product manuals, code documentation, and support systems.\n\n## RAG pipeline\n\n1. Ingest files.\n2. Extract text.\n3. Clean and chunk text.\n4. Create embeddings.\n5. Store chunks in vector database.\n6. On query, retrieve top-k chunks.\n7. Optionally rerank.\n8. Build prompt with context.\n9. Ask LLM.\n10. Return answer with citations/sources.\n\n## Chunking strategy\n\nBad chunking creates bad retrieval. Consider:\n\n- chunk size;\n- overlap;\n- headings/section boundaries;\n- metadata like source, page, URL, timestamp;\n- code block preservation;\n- table extraction;\n- language-specific tokenization.\n\n## LangChain\n\nLangChain is a framework for building LLM applications with components for prompts, models, retrievers, tools, chains, agents, memory, and structured outputs.\n\nGood use:\n\n- quick orchestration;\n- tool calling;\n- retrieval chains;\n- structured output with Pydantic;\n- prototypes that later become production services.\n\nAvoid hiding all logic inside a giant agent. Keep business-critical logic explicit.\n\n## LangGraph\n\nLangGraph helps build graph-based LLM workflows where state moves between nodes.\n\nUse it for:\n\n- multi-step deterministic + LLM flows;\n- agent loops with guardrails;\n- human-in-the-loop review;\n- retries and branching;\n- multi-agent coordination.\n\n## Structured output\n\nUse structured output when your app needs JSON-like reliable data.\n\n```python\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel, Field\n\nclass BookInfo(BaseModel):\n    title: str\n    author: str\n    summary: str\n    sources: list[str] = Field(default_factory=list)\n```\n\nPrompt principle:\n\n```text\nReturn only data that fits the schema.\nIf a field is unknown, return null or an empty list according to schema.\nDo not invent URLs.\n```\n\n## Tool calling\n\nA tool is a function the model can request, such as search, database lookup, calculator, or internal API call.\n\nProduction rules:\n\n- validate tool inputs;\n- limit tool permissions;\n- log tool calls;\n- handle timeouts;\n- do not expose secrets;\n- do not let tool output bypass authorization.\n\n## Multi-agent systems\n\nMulti-agent systems split responsibilities:\n\n```text\nPlanner agent -> decides steps\nResearch agent -> searches/retrieves\nCoder agent -> writes code\nReviewer agent -> checks result\nGuardrail node -> validates safety/schema\n```\n\nUse agents only when dynamic decision-making is needed. For deterministic workflows, normal code or LangGraph nodes are often safer.\n\n## Common mistakes\n\n1. Treating RAG as “just vector search”.\n2. Not storing source metadata.\n3. Returning answers without citations for private docs.\n4. Using too-large chunks that dilute relevance.\n5. Letting agents call powerful tools without guardrails.\n6. Assuming structured output is perfect; always validate.\n7. Not evaluating answers against test questions.\n\n## Production best practices\n\n- Add retrieval evaluation dataset.\n- Store chunk IDs and source references.\n- Use hybrid search where needed.\n- Use reranking for precision.\n- Apply prompt injection defenses for retrieved text.\n- Log prompt, retrieval IDs, model, latency, token usage.\n- Cache common retrieval/answers carefully.\n- Validate structured outputs with Pydantic.\n- Keep deterministic business rules outside the model.\n\n## Interview-style explanation\n\n> RAG retrieves relevant private/current context and gives it to the LLM so the answer is grounded. I design ingestion, chunking, embeddings, vector storage, retrieval, reranking, prompt construction, and citations. LangChain can wire models, retrievers, and tools; LangGraph is better for stateful multi-step workflows. For production I validate structured outputs, add guardrails, log sources, and evaluate retrieval quality.\n\n## Additional Concepts Added\n\n- **Hybrid search**: combines keyword and vector retrieval.\n- **Reranking**: improves top-k context relevance.\n- **Prompt injection**: retrieved documents may contain malicious instructions; treat retrieved text as data, not instruction.\n- **MCP servers**: standardized tool/context servers that expose capabilities to AI clients."
